<HEADLINE>
<P>
NISSAN TO HIKE PURCHASE OF U.S., FOREIGN PARTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Nissan Motor Co. announced Friday that it would sharply increase the amount of 
foreign- and U.S.-made auto parts it buys, becoming the first Japanese auto 
maker to announce goals for such purchases. 
</P>
<P>
 Nissan said it will purchase about $4.3 billion in foreign-made auto parts 
over the next four years, Japan's Jiji Press reported. U.S.-made auto parts 
will account for $3.4 billion of the total, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
 Nissan, the world's fourth largest auto maker, said the plan is conditional 
upon the ability of its American production affiliates to run at full capacity 
and increased efficiency, Jiji said. 
</P>
<P>
 Japan's Ministry of International Trade and Industry has urged Japanese auto 
makers to import a greater share of their auto components from abroad to dampen 
trade friction. U.S. officials have criticized Japan for its relatively low 
level of imported auto parts. 
</P>
