<HEADLINE>
<P>
VALLEY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By David E. Brady 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 WANTED MAN: Authorities trying to prosecute an Encino attorney on murder 
charges in connection with deliberate traffic accidents got a big break: 
Houston police nabbed a man sought as the suspected "capper," the long-sought 
link between the attorney and ring members who positioned their cars to be hit 
by trucks on the Golden State Freeway for insurance payments (B1). 
</P>
<P>
 BAD BREAKS: Valley business owners have had a run of bad luck lately.First the 
quake, and now a rash of armed robberies -- more than half of them aimed at dry 
cleaners (B1). . . . Still, it's not all that unusual for criminals to target a 
specific type of store. In past years, serial arsonists have struck at Valley 
nail salons and barbershops. 
</P>
<P>
 SMALL BUT STRONG: Well known for its large Christian population, the Antelope 
Valley is also home to an active Jewish community. Temple Beth Knesset 
Bamidbar, founded 43 years ago in Lancaster, may draw far fewer people than 
other places of worship, but for many Jews it is the center of the area's 
religious life (B1). . . . "If you're Jewish, it's the only game in town," said 
one member. David E. Brady 
</P>
</TEXT>
